<p>The autocorrelation function reveals strong temporal dependence in hourly electricity demand. Autocorrelation is highest at short lags, indicating that demand in a given hour is strongly related to demand in preceding hours. Pronounced spikes occur at regular 24-hour intervals (24, 48, 72 hours and so on), demonstrating strong daily seasonality. Additional peaks are visible at 168 and 336 hours, corresponding to one and two weeks respectively, confirming the presence of weekly seasonal patterns. The recurrence of these peaks suggests that demand profiles are highly predictable from previous days and weeks.</p>
<p>Almost all autocorrelation coefficients remain above the significance bounds, indicating that historical demand contains substantial predictive information. The strong daily and weekly seasonal structure observed in the ACF supports the use of seasonal forecasting models such as Seasonal Naive, ETS and ARIMA, which can account for these recurring patterns.</p>
</section>
<section id="forecasting" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="forecasting">Forecasting<a class="anchorjs-link " aria-label="Anchor" data-anchorjs-icon="" href="https://melfitzsimmons-rstudio.tools.analytical-platform.service.justice.gov.uk/files/Time%20Series%20Practice/Electricity_demand_project.html#forecasting" style="font: 1em / 1 anchorjs-icons; margin-left: 0.1875em; padding-right: 0.1875em; padding-left: 0.1875em;"></a></h2>
<p>To identify an appropriate benchmark model, seasonal naive forecasts were evaluated using time series cross-validation. Given the strong seasonal patterns observed during the exploratory analysis, models based on daily, weekly and yearly lags were compared.</p>
<section id="seasonal-naive-cross-validation" class="level3">
