<section id="comparison-with-ets-and-arima-models" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="comparison-with-ets-and-arima-models">Comparison with ETS And ARIMA models<a class="anchorjs-link " aria-label="Anchor" data-anchorjs-icon="" href="https://melfitzsimmons-rstudio.tools.analytical-platform.service.justice.gov.uk/files/Time%20Series%20Practice/Electricity_demand_project.html#comparison-with-ets-and-arima-models" style="font: 1em / 1 anchorjs-icons; margin-left: 0.1875em; padding-right: 0.1875em; padding-left: 0.1875em;"></a></h2>
<p>Following the evaluation of seasonal naive benchmark models, more advanced forecasting approaches were considered. Exponential Smoothing State Space (ETS) and AutoRegressive Integrated Moving Average (ARIMA) models were fitted and compared against the seasonal naive benchmark.</p>
<p>To evaluate forecast performance, the data were divided into training and test sets. The most recent two weeks of observations were reserved as a holdout test set, while the preceding two years of data were used for model estimation. Cross-validation was not used due to memory constraints.</p>
