<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="conclusion">Conclusion<a class="anchorjs-link " aria-label="Anchor" data-anchorjs-icon="" href="https://melfitzsimmons-rstudio.tools.analytical-platform.service.justice.gov.uk/files/Time%20Series%20Practice/Electricity_demand_project.html#conclusion" style="font: 1em / 1 anchorjs-icons; margin-left: 0.1875em; padding-right: 0.1875em; padding-left: 0.1875em;"></a></h2>
<p>This project developed and evaluated forecasting models for hourly electricity demand in Victoria’s National Electricity Market. Exploratory analysis revealed strong daily and weekly seasonal patterns, which were confirmed through autocorrelation analysis.</p>
<p>Seasonal naive benchmark models were compared using time series cross-validation, with the weekly seasonal naive model providing the strongest benchmark performance.</p>
<p>When compared against ETS and ARIMA models on a two-week holdout sample, the weekly seasonal naive model achieved the lowest RMSE and MAPE, indicating the best overall forecast accuracy. This suggests that electricity demand is highly dependent on demand observed during the corresponding hour of the previous week.</p>
<p>Future work could incorporate exogenous predictors such as temperature, weather conditions, public holidays and economic activity to improve forecast performance.</p>
